The issue with the current implementation is that it is only searching for the presence of the keywords "TABLE" and "COLUMNS" in the text. However, it is not considering the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns.

To address this issue, we can modify the function to analyze the structure of the text to determine if it represents a table or columns. We can look for patterns such as rows of data with consistent column separators or headers for each column to identify a table or columns.

Let's update the function to implement this improved logic:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n').map(line => line.trim());

  // Check if the text represents a table
  if (lines.length >= 3) {
    const headerRow = lines[1].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the second line by multiple spaces
    const dataRow = lines[2].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the third line by multiple spaces
    if (headerRow.length === dataRow.length) {
      return "TABLE";
    }
  }

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const columnHeaders = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/); // Split the first line by multiple spaces
  if (columnHeaders.length > 1) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // If the text does not match the table or column structure, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

By analyzing the structure of the text data, we can determine whether it represents a table, columns, both, or neither based on the presence of consistent column separators and headers.

The mistake in the previous implementation is that it assumed that a table should have a header row and a data row, and the number of columns should be consistent throughout the rows. However, in the example input, the table structure might not strictly follow these assumptions.

To address this issue, we need to update the function to analyze the structure of the text more flexibly. We can consider the presence of consistent column separators and a reasonable number of columns to determine if it represents a table or columns.

Here's the updated function to handle the input more accurately:

```javascript
function doesItContainTableOrColumns(text) {
  // Split the text into lines
  const lines = text.split('\n').map(line => line.trim());

  // Check if the text represents a table
  if (lines.length >= 3) {
    const dataRows = lines.slice(2); // Exclude the first two lines as they are headers
    const columnCounts = dataRows.map(row => row.split(/\s{2,}/).length); // Count the number of columns in each data row
    const columnCountSet = new Set(columnCounts); // Use a set to get unique column counts
    if (columnCountSet.size === 1) {
      return "TABLE";
    }
  }

  // Check if the text represents columns
  const columnHeaders = lines[0].split(/\s{2,}/);
  if (columnHeaders.length > 1) {
    return "COLUMNS";
  }

  // If the text does not match the table or column structure, return "NORMAL"
  return "NORMAL";
}
```

This updated function now considers the presence of consistent column separators in the data rows to determine if it represents a table. If the number of columns in the data rows is consistent, it will identify the text as a table. If the first line contains multiple columns, it will be identified as columns. If neither of these conditions is met, it will be classified as "NORMAL".
